What is money?
Cash, dosh, mulah, cheese, paper, the filthy lucre, wedge, and of course the root of all evil: there are plenty of pseudonyms for money, but when defining in exact terms, it's meaning is a little more elusive.
                    <br>
                    <br>

Is it the coins in your pocket?  Is it the balance figure on your bank statement? Is the $US1.5 trillion that was created by a few keystrokes on a computer at the Federal Reserve Bank of America in 2008 to bailout the banking system?  These differing examples seem right, so a proper definition must be broad enough to capture them as well as all of the other practical examples you might think of. So let's simply define money as a way of assigning an agreed value to goods and services so that they can be exchanged between people.
 <br>
<br>

You can exchange the coins in your pocket for a lollipop.  You look at your bank balance and judge whether you have enough to exchange it for a horse or car or a can of baked beans. And the officer at the Fed who placed over a trillion dollars in the bank accounts of America’s largest financial institutions was expecting that in exchange they would avoid the collapse of the world’s economy. Bargain!
                    <br>
                    <br>

There is an interesting fiction in the concept of money:  it only works if we all believe it works. In Yuval Noah Harahi’s excellent book “Sapiens” he calls the development of money a “purely mental revolution. It involved the creation of a new inter-subjective reality that exists solely in the people’s shared imagination”. In other words, if you believe a pint of Guinness can be exchanged for a €5 note and the bartender believes it as well, then sláinte, the system works!
<br>
<br>
More on this subject:  listen to this podcast https://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/423/the-invention-of-money
                    <br>
                    <br>

Enter the cryptocurrency
                    <br>
                    <br>
In 2008 a mysterious whitepaper appeared on The Cryptography Mailing list at metzdowd.com.  Nothing mysterious about the content of the article, but with the person (or persons) who wrote it. Its author was Satoshi Nakamoto: an unfamiliar name in a community where unfamiliarity was unusual, particularly as the titular “Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System” paper seemed to arrive as a fully-formed and thoroughly tested solution for something that many in the community had tried to build before and had failed: a robust, cryptographic, trustless, decentralised electronic money system.
                    <br>
                    <br>

The whitepaper outlined how transactions could be clumped into a block, which was then stamped with a hashed cryptographic identification and placed at the end of chain of previously created blocks, with the prior block’s id baked into its own. This would ensure that transactions of a certain “depth” would be practically impossible to alter: so everyone could trust that the transactions were accurate, irrefutable and immutable.
<br>
<br>
And so was born bitcoin and the "blockchain" and an overnight sensation a decade in the making.  The whitepaper spawned whole new industries, billions of dollars of investment and inspired innovation in diverse and hitherto unrelated fields.  It has also, inevitably, inspired fraudsters, charlatans and hackers to steal huge amounts from naive and badly advised citizens.
                    <br>
                    <br>

Further reading: you can actually read the whitepaper here: https://bitcoin.org/bitcoin.pdf
Or for a good historical account of how bitcoin developed there is an excellent Netflix documentary called “Banking on Bitcoin” 
