How does KPcoin work?
                <br>
                <br>
KPcoin is essentially the same as bitcoin: it uses a library attached to the core bitcoin software designed to work with Node.JS, which is language that the website is written in. This library is known as bcoin (LINK).  Bcoin in its turn uses the the core bitcoin software as its base - so there is a direct technical link between KPcoin and the bitcoin software. See the below for a deeper analysis of bitcoin and the key differences between bitcoin and KPcoin. In this section we'll go through what is happening when you log into the KPcoin website, view your wallet, make a transactions, and the steps the KPcoin network takes to validate that transaction.
        <br>
        <br>
Primer:
       <br>
Public key cryptography (LINK) is the foundation of ownership on the bitcoin and KPcoin network. As it applies here, and in very basic terms, you have two keys: a private key and a public key. An amount of value being sent to you is "locked" by the sender by tagging it with your public key, and can only be "unlocked" (i.e. spent) by the person who holds the private key. Your public key is public and private key should be...well...you guessed it: private. Your balance is simply the total of unspent transactions you have associated with your . 
      <br>
        <br>
                    
The most important part of the bitcoin protocol is the transaction (which you will sometimes see referred to as TX): they track and store the value of currency that belongs to the private key's owner, they are the basis of blocks in the block chain and they generate a reward to a "miner" who confirms the transaction on behalf of the network.
        <br>
        <br>
In order to initiate or receive a transaction you need to have an application called a "wallet".  These can be thought of the digital equivalent of a real-world wallet (or purse), but this is only really for convenience - most wallet applications can and do perform many more tasks. Probably the most odd thing about a cryptocurrency wallet is that is really is just an abstraction of your private key.  You can have as many wallets as you want, but the amount of money is linked to your private key. If you set up 10 different wallets with the same private key you don't get 10x your balance!  All you're doing is making your wallet link with your transaction history which is stored on the blockchain. 
                    
<br>
    <br> 
When receiving money, the sender will simply tag the output of the transaction with your public key, which everyone on the network has can see and has access to. However if you want to go on and spend the proceeds of that transaction, only the person who has access to the associated private key can do so. When sending money, or making a purchase you will have to find a transaction (or multiple transactions) that add up to more than than the purchase price, tag it with the recipient's public key and "unlock" the previous transaction/s with your private key. Luckily a wallet will scan your available unspent outputs and form a transaction in accordance with the rules of the protocol: you don't have to do any clever programming, the wallet does it all for you!
<br>
    <br>
You could build your own wallet software, but in order to successfully transact you'd have to make sure it can construct transations properly. If you are using bitcoin it is far easier (and safer) just to download a reputable wallet - the bitcoin.org website is excellent starting place when choosing one(LINK). 
<br> 
        <br> 
KPcoin comes with a web wallet hosted on the website for you - in fact that's the only type of wallet you can use with KPcoin as it is a closed system (see the differences between bitcoin and KPcoin below).  This is normally not recommended as it means your private key is stored on someone else's system. On the plus side it usually means that you don't have to worry about losing your private key - as the website will usually keep back ups, but it does mean you have to trust that the website company will be able to keep your data safe. On the personal side you can have a wallet on your phone, on a USB stick, a piece of paper or even in your brain (by memorising a pass phrase). Although technically the last two are just examples of storing your private key offline: in order to transact you will still need some sort of wallet software connected to the network.  With a personal wallet the safekeeping of your private key is entirely your responsbility.
    <br>
    <br>    
A "full node" is a computer that runs a full version of the bitcoin or KPcoin protocol, keeps a copy of the history of all transactions and connects to other nodes in the network to inform them of transactions and validate other node's blocks. 
      <br>
    <br>                
"Miners", who are also known as bookkeepers, usually run a full node as they need the most comprehensive and up-to-date version of the transaction history so the can build new unconfirmed transactions into blocks. After assembling a candidate block, the miner enters a race with other miners to find a number lower than than that of the network's target. This target is aquired through repeated attempts at hashing the block's header (which includes the previous block's hash number), which produces a random number and by adding and iterating a variable number (called a nonce) trillions of times a second, new attempts at reaching the target are made. They repeat until they're lucky enough to get under the target, or if they get notification from another miner that they've been successful (at which point they give up on this race, and move on to the next). If they win the race they announce it to all other miners, who validate the result and the block is then placed at the tip of the blockchain. The miner can now include a special transaction (called a coinbase transaction) in the block where they reward themselves with bitcoin (essentially creating money). The randomness of the target number means the miners have to do work to find it, and since it is performed according to the rules of the network and is validated by the other miners, it can be proved.  This is why it is called "Proof-of-Work".
<br>
<br>
Since the winning hash number includes the previous block's hash number, blocks can only ever be in sequence. Given the difficulty and work that goes into finding the target number, the sequence is impossible to break or forge. If two miners happen to find hash number at the same time, then there will temporarily be a fork in the chain. However whoever wins the next block will chose the spur of the fork that they will build on (by choosing one of the forked block's hash number to include in their candidate block header) and the other block will be orphaned.  Any non-duplicated transactions from this orphaned block go back into the unconfirmed transaction pot and will be picked up again in the next round. 
