Bitcoin analysed:
                     <br>
                    <br>
There are four main elements to bitcoin: the software - known as the bitcoin protocol.  The blockchain - which is the public ledger which the network uses to log all transactions. The consensus rules - the way which independent members of the network agree on the validity of transactions and issuance of coins and the Proof-of-Work alogrithm - a way of ensuring the integrity of the blockchain.
                     <br>
                    <br>
                    
The software:<br>
The bitcoin protocol was defined initially by Satoshi Nakamoto in the original bitcoin whitepaper, but the ongoing stewardship is performed by group of volunteers.  It is an open-source software hosted on GitHub (LINK!!), which means anyone can download the software and play with it, but the master version is controlled by a core development team. Anyone can suggest changes, which are vetted by the core team and if the changes are "sensible" they are proposed to the network as Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIPS). "The network" in the case is everybody who uses bitcoin, but to think that this is a completely egalitarian situation where every one has the same amount of influence is euphemistic: those companies who run big exchanges or mining pools have more of a say in the implemenation of any BIPS.   
<br><br>
                    
As with most human endeavours that involve large groups, there are differences of opinion. Probably the most famous example is the problem of the block size on the bitcoin blockchain, where lines are drawn between those who believe a larger block size is essential for speeding up transaction confirmations, and those who reject it on the grounds that this would cause extra storage costs and goes against some of the core principals that Satoshi outlined in her whitepaper. There have already been two bitcoin-based cryptocurrencies with their own blockchains (bitgold and bitcash) that have gone off on their own "forks" to solve the dispute, but in BIP141 - "Segregated Witness" there has been a proposal to change the native bitcoin blockchain to allow a larger block size, and separate out the digital signature part of the transaction to free up even more space. As at the time of writing it is not clear that all of the miners on the bitcoin network would accept this change, which would lead to dangerous split, which at the least would cause confusion and at worst lead to a full abandonment of the protocol.                  
 <br>
<br>
