<br>
<br>
The bitcoin software is, in comparison to most widespread applications, very simple: this is deliberate to make it more resistant to hacking. In fact some of the architecture date back to the 1970s, and while this reduced complexity reduces the number of possible applications that can be built on the system, it increases it's robustness.  Ethereum conversely allows entire software applications to be built on its blockchain by anyone, which gives it much more flexibility, but introduces many more points of attack by malicious actors.  Given that bitcoin is a store of value (and for some lucky early adopters, quite a large store!), compulsorily peer-to-peer, open to all, it's resistance to attack is of huge importance.
        
  
 <br>
<br>
The blockchain:<br>
Distributed databases and distributed ledger technology is not new. Anytime you've shared a spreadsheet via email you say that you have created you're own distributed database, although a fairly clunky one that is difficult govern and control (if you have ever done this in real life you'll know what I mean). One of the great innovations in the whitepaper was to clump transactions into blocks of data, sign those blocks with a hashed id, and then use that id as part the hashed id of the next block: creating a sequence that cannot be refuted or broken. Creating discrete blocks of data like this is certainly not the best way to design a database, but the genius of this invention is  gives you the *possibility* of protecting the data in the blocks, and *possibility* of full integrity over the full sequence of blocks. 
                    
However on its own a blockchain doesn't ensure immutability and integrity - for that you need a little more cryptography thrown in.
<br>
<br>
                    
Consensus rules: <br>
The validity of the blocks being created is of primary concern to the network.  No-one wants to be diddled, but at the same time they want to be able to play the game.  With that in mind the code that bitcoin is based on is actually very simple With the introduction of cryptography into the bitcoin protocol we have a way of making it impossible to cheat (ok, ok - properly speaking "improbable", but the chances of you breaking the cryptography in bitcoin makes your chances of winning all of the lotteries in the world, on the same day, while wearing a pink fedora, a shoo-in).
 <br>
<br>
Proof-of-Work: <br>
The central characteristic of cryptography is the trapdoor: it's very easy to turn a dial one way, but impossible to turn it the other. With the hashing alogrithims used in bitcoin (SHA-256 for the most part), this is very much the ratchet affect in action.  When creating a the hashed id for a block, the miner will use the data in the block's header (which includes the version of software, the previous block id, a timestamp and a variable number) to create the hash (a hexadecimal number with 256-bits in length). In order to the win the block prize, the miner must plug in a different number to the variable number field over and over again until they "happen" upon the number below the network target.  Once this number is found, it is very easy to prove that its correct (just tell the other miners what variable number you used), but impossible to predict a number that would work.


                    
                    
