How does KPcoin differ from Bitcoin?
                    <br>
                    <br>
There are not many differences between KPcoin and Bitcoin, given that they are based off the same core software code. There is the same limit of supply (21,000,000) and the same denomination: the smallest unit is 100 millionth of a full coin, the way transactions are signed and the fact that you can exchange coins for assets is also consistent, however there are some important differences:
                    <br>

Bitcoin is called Bitcoin and KPcoin is called KPcoin:  Obvious, but worth pointing out given one of the most important steps in creating a cryptocurrency is to brand it.
                    <br>

Getting Bitcoin costs money, KPcoin is free: Unless you have a generous donor, bitcoins cost money and are usually purchased at an online exchange.  KPcoin is free and you receive them simply by logging into the website.
                    <br>

Bitcoin is decentralised. KPcoin is centralised: Where anyone can download the core bitcoin software, obtain a copy of the full ledger of transactions and become a “miner”. KPcoin is wholly controlled by me, Peter Thompson aka KiwiPedro and I act like a central bank.  A very generous (irresponsible?) central bank it has to be said.
                    <br>

You can transfer Bitcoins to other Bitcoin users. You cannot transfer KPcoins.  You can buy digital assets with both versions, but I’ve decided, for privacy reasons, not allow users to transfer coins
                    <br>

Bitcoin has many types of Wallets. KPcoin only has a Web Wallet:   With bitcoin you can effectively have a wallet in your brain:  if you memorise the pass phrases which derive your private key, then you could at any time install some software and enter those phrases and get access to your unspent outputs.  There are paper wallets, USB wallets and online web wallets available for bitcoin.  For simplicity, KPcoin just has the latter.
